## Step 2
The probability of a match on the $i$th draw, denoted by event $A_i$, can be calculated by considering the total number of ways to arrange $n$ balls and the number of arrangements where the $i$th ball is in its correct position.

## Step 3
For a specific $i$, the probability of $A_i$ happening is $\frac{(n-1)!}{n!} = \frac{1}{n}$ because there are $(n-1)!$ ways to arrange the remaining $n-1$ balls after fixing the $i$th ball in its correct position, out of $n!$ total arrangements.

## Step 4
The probability of at least one match occurring can be found using the principle of inclusion-exclusion. The formula involves summing the probabilities of individual matches, subtracting the probabilities of intersections of pairs of matches, adding back the probabilities of intersections of triples of matches, and so on.

## Step 5
The probability of at least one match is given by $P(A_1 \cup A_2 \cup ... \cup A_n) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} P(A_i) - \sum_{i<j} P(A_i \cap A_j) + \sum_{i<j<k} P(A_i \cap A_j \cap A_k) - ... + (-1)^{n+1}P(A_1 \cap A_2 \cap ... \cap A_n)$.

